This is a classic client-side rendering error. The `TypeError: Cannot read properties of undefined (reading 'some')` indicates that a piece of code is trying to use an array method (`.some()`) on a variable that hasn't been initialized yet and is therefore `undefined`.

Looking at the code, the most likely culprit is in the `login/page.tsx` file. The `signInWithGoogle` function contains this logic:

```typescript
if (error.code === 'auth/unauthorized-domain') {
  // ...
} else if (error.code === 'auth/popup-closed-by-user') {
  // ...
}
else {
   // This part is problematic
   toast({
    variant: "destructive",
    title: "Sign-In Error",
    description: "An unexpected error occurred during sign-in. Please check the console for more details.",
  });
}
```

The problem is that the final `else` block does not check if the user is simply cancelling the sign-in process. The `toast` function itself might be triggering downstream effects that lead to this `.some()` error. My previous fix to the error handling was incomplete. I need to make the error handling more specific and robust.

I will update the `catch` block in `src/app/login/page.tsx` to more gracefully handle different types of sign-in errors, including when a user simply closes the pop-up window, which will prevent this runtime error from occurring.

